vers the many mixed messages they purvey: for example, females can be leaders—but male leadership ought to be the norm; stereotyping is wrong—but black means evil; historical truth is valued—but only tell what one can sell, etc. Adding these messages together, Ward raises important questions about the moral ambiguity of Disney's overall worldview and demonstrates the need for parents to be discerning in letting their children learn moral values and life lessons from Disney films.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAnimated filmszUnited StatesxThemes, motives. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aChristians, Clifford G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristians, Clifford.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798663423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798663/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK